            <section class="water-seo-section">
                <h2 class="water-section-heading">FAQs</h2>
                <div class="water-content-grid">
                    <div class="water-content-card">
                        <h3>‚ùì How accurate is this calculator?</h3>
                        <p>
                            Our calculator uses the scientifically validated formula: Calories = (Time √ó MET √ó 3.5 √ó Weight) √∑ 200, with MET values from the Compendium of Physical Activities. This provides accuracy within 10-15%, comparable to laboratory measurements.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="water-content-card">
                        <h3>üåä Why does water depth matter?</h3>
                        <p>
                            Water depth directly impacts resistance. Chest-deep water increases energy expenditure by 25% compared to waist-deep water because more body surface area must overcome water resistance with each movement. Neck-deep water adds up to 35% more calorie burn.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="water-content-card">
                        <h3>üíß Is water walking good for weight loss?</h3>
                        <p>
                            Yes! Water walking burns 300-500 calories per hour while being gentle on joints. Regular sessions (30-45 minutes, 4-5 times weekly) combined with proper nutrition contribute significantly to weight loss. Use our <a href="https://fitliferegime.com/weight-loss-calorie-calculator/" rel="dofollow" target="_blank">weight loss calculator</a> for personalized goals.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="water-content-card">
                        <h3>üèä Water running vs water walking?</h3>
                        <p>
                            Water running burns 50-100% more calories than water walking. A 70 kg person burns approximately 350 cal/hour water walking but 480-720 cal/hour water running. Both provide excellent low-impact workouts, but water running delivers higher calorie burn in less time.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <div class="water-disclaimer">
                <h3>üèä Exercise & Health Disclaimer</h3>
                <p> Water exercise is generally safe for most people,
                    but always consult with healthcare professionals, certified aquatic fitness instructors, or physical therapists before beginning intensive water exercise programs,
                    especially if you have pre-existing health conditions, injuries, or cannot swim. Never exercise alone in water. This tool is for educational and informational purposes only.
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
